---

<CalculatorLayout calculator={calculator} cluster={cluster} intro={intro} lastUpdated={lastUpdated} authorName={authorName} authorUrl={authorUrl} shareImage={shareImage}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(howToJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(personJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(softwareAppJsonLd)} slot="head" />

  <!-- Desktop sticky TOC in the right sidebar column -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="sidebar" slot="sidebar" />

  <!-- Both calculator sections — immediately after intro, visible without scrolling -->
  <RainBarrelCalculator client:load />

  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-500">
    Collected water needs somewhere to go — see our <a href="/calculators/drip-irrigation-calculator/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Drip Irrigation Calculator</a> next.
  </p>

  <!-- Mobile TOC accordion — below the calculator, collapsed by default, hidden on desktop -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="accordion" />

  <LeadMagnetForm
    client:load
    listId={leadMagnet.listId}
    clusterName={leadMagnet.clusterName}
    icon={leadMagnet.icon}
    description={`A one-page PDF of the ${cluster.name.toLowerCase()} math from this site, emailed once.`}
  />

  <article class="prose prose-bark mt-8 max-w-none prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-bark-900 prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:scroll-mt-24 prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:font-semibold prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:font-semibold prose-a:text-moss-700 prose-strong:text-bark-900">
    <h2 id="how-to-use-this-calculator">How to Use This Calculator</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Enter your roof area and rainfall amount.</li>
      <li>Read your total gallons collected and recommended barrel count.</li>
      <li>Enter your barrel height in the water pressure section.</li>
      <li>Read your spigot water pressure in PSI.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="how-much-rainwater-can-you-collect">How Much Rainwater Can You Collect?</h2>
    <p>
      Collection comes down to three numbers: your <strong>roof area</strong>, the <strong>rainfall amount</strong>, and a <strong>collection efficiency</strong> that accounts for real-world losses. The conversion itself is simple &mdash; 1 inch of rain over 1 sq ft of roof yields <strong>0.623 gallons</strong> &mdash; but not every drop that hits your roof ends up in the barrel.
    </p>
    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/rain-barrel-calculator-roof-collection.svg"
        alt="Rain flowing off a roof through a gutter into a rain barrel with a spigot near the base"
        width="400"
        height="250"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        Gutters, downspouts, and barrel overflow all take a bite out of the theoretical maximum.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Collection efficiency (85% by default in the calculator above) accounts for evaporation off the roof surface, water lost to gutter overflow during heavy rain, splash-out at downspout junctions, and any first-flush diverter that intentionally routes the first bit of runoff away from the barrel. Steeper roofs and well-maintained gutters trend toward the higher end of realistic efficiency; roofs with debris or undersized gutters trend lower. 85% is a reasonable planning default, not a guarantee.
    </p>

    <h2 id="how-much-water-pressure-will-you-get">How Much Water Pressure Will You Get?</h2>
    <p>
      A rain barrel has no pump &mdash; whatever pressure comes out of the spigot is purely <strong>hydrostatic pressure</strong>, generated by the weight of the water above the outlet. The relationship is direct: every foot of water height above the spigot adds <strong>0.433 PSI</strong>. There&rsquo;s no way around this without adding a pump; a bigger barrel doesn&rsquo;t give you more pressure unless it&rsquo;s also taller or elevated higher.
    </p>
    <p>
      In practice, this means most rain barrel setups produce very low pressure &mdash; a barrel on a 2&ndash;3 ft stand yields roughly 1&ndash;1.5 PSI. That&rsquo;s workable for gravity-fed drip irrigation and soaker hoses, which need very little pressure to function. It is not enough for a standard sprinkler, which typically needs <strong>15&ndash;30 PSI</strong> to spray properly &mdash; getting there from a barrel alone means adding an inline booster pump.
    </p>

    <h2 id="is-collecting-rainwater-legal-in-your-area">Is Collecting Rainwater Legal in Your Area?</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Rainwater collection is legal in all 50 U.S. states</strong> &mdash; no state bans it outright. A small number of states have specific rules worth knowing before you set up a system:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Colorado:</strong> households may use up to <strong>two rain barrels with a combined capacity of 110 gallons</strong>, for outdoor, non-potable use only (lawn, garden, and similar irrigation on the same property where the water was collected), and the barrels must have a <strong>sealable lid</strong>. This is current as of House Bill 16-1005 (2016). Residents with an exempt well permit may qualify to collect more under a separate permit — see the Colorado sources below.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Utah:</strong> properties may store up to <strong>2,500 gallons</strong> of collected rainwater. Free registration with the Utah Division of Water Rights is required once storage exceeds a small threshold (two 100-gallon containers or less needs no registration).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Everywhere else:</strong> most states and localities have no specific rainwater collection restrictions beyond general property and building codes, but rules can change and vary by city or HOA. Check your local and state regulations before installing a large system — this page isn&rsquo;t a substitute for that check.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm text-bark-500">
      <em>Last verified: {legalLastVerified}. Water law changes over time and by jurisdiction — verify current rules for your specific location before relying on this summary.</em>
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example">Worked Examples</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Collection:</strong> a <strong>1,200 sq ft roof</strong> gets <strong>1 inch</strong> of rain, at the default <strong>85%</strong> collection efficiency.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Base conversion:</strong> 1,200 sq ft &times; 1 in &times; 0.623 = <strong>747.6 gallons</strong> (theoretical maximum).</li>
      <li><strong>Apply efficiency:</strong> 747.6 &times; 0.85 = <strong>~635.5 gallons</strong> actually collected.</li>
      <li><strong>Barrels needed:</strong> 635.5 &divide; 50 = 12.7 &rarr; round up to <strong>13 standard 50-gallon barrels</strong>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      <strong>Water pressure:</strong> a barrel elevated on a stand puts the water surface <strong>3 ft</strong> above the spigot.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>PSI:</strong> 0.433 &times; 3 ft = <strong>~1.3 PSI</strong> &mdash; enough for gravity-fed drip irrigation, not a sprinkler.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Assuming 100% collection efficiency.</strong> Real-world losses from evaporation, gutter overflow, and splash-out are significant. Planning around the theoretical maximum instead of a realistic efficiency (80&ndash;90%) leads to underbuilt storage.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring first-flush contamination.</strong> The first runoff off a roof carries accumulated dust, bird droppings, and roofing debris. Without a first-flush diverter, that contaminated water goes straight into your barrel — don&rsquo;t use unfiltered rain barrel water on edible plants without accounting for this.</li>
      <li><strong>Expecting sprinkler-level pressure from gravity alone.</strong> A barrel on a stand produces roughly 1&ndash;1.5 PSI, nowhere near the 15&ndash;30 PSI a standard sprinkler needs. A booster pump, not a taller stand, is the practical fix.</li>
    </ul>

    <FAQBlock id="rain-barrel-calculator-faq" heading="Rain Barrel Calculator FAQ" faqs={faqs} />

    <h2 id="sources-and-further-reading">Sources &amp; further reading</h2>
    <p>
      Legal information on this page draws on the Colorado Division of Water Resources&rsquo; <a href="https://dwr.colorado.gov/services/water-administration/rainwater-storm-water-graywater" rel="noopener">&ldquo;Rainwater, Storm Water &amp; Graywater&rdquo;</a> page and Colorado State University Extension&rsquo;s <a href="https://extension.colostate.edu/resource/rainwater-collection-in-colorado/" rel="noopener">&ldquo;Rainwater Collection in Colorado&rdquo;</a> fact sheet. For more on how we source and review the formulas behind every calculator, see our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <RelatedCalculatorsList id="related-calculators" items={[
      { name: 'Watering & Irrigation cluster', url: '/clusters/watering-and-irrigation/', anchorText: 'see our complete guide to rainwater collection and drip delivery', note: 'how collection and delivery work together, plus soil infiltration rates that affect run time.' },
      { name: 'Drip Irrigation Calculator', url: '/calculators/drip-irrigation-calculator/', note: 'collected water needs somewhere to go — figure out run time and delivery here.' },
    ]} />

    <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-bark-500">
      Last updated: {formattedDate}.
    </p>
  </article>
</CalculatorLayout>
